Hey, this looks great all of it, but if I may propose, how about making the factory and the wrapper class separate? Curious for arguments for and against. Then that would take the `_initialize_app()` method outside of this class. 

I think it could make it easier like this for example: 

```python
class PypiserverApp:
    def __init__(self, config: RunConfig) -> None:
        # without any reference to Bottle here
        self.config = config
        self.auth = functools.partial(auth, config)
   
     def log_request(self) -> None:
        log.info(self.config.log_req_frmt, request.environ)
     
     # and so forth with the other hook methods...

class PypiserverAppFactory:

    @classmethod
    def build_app(cls, config: RunConfig, app: Bottle) -> Bottle:
        pypiserver_app = PypiserverApp(config)
        return cls._initialize_app(app, pypiserver_app)

   @staticmethod
    def _initialize_app(app: Bottle, pypiserver_app) -> Bottle:
        app.hook("before_request")(pypiserver_app.log_request)
        app.hook("before_request")(pypiserver_app.parse_request_path)
        # and so on...
        app._pypiserver_config = config
        return app
```
Then potentially, later this would allow extending the `pypiserver` with ohther backends for people who could want it, if instead of `app: Bottle` the parameter will be `builder: AppBuilder` or so that will be an instance of a strategy to initialize an app of a particular backend given the pypiserver wrapper. But that's a bit too far off maybe. Let me know :)

