In fact it is correct because the strings that are written by the Ada code generator are UTF-8.

The root issue is that the `char` is signed and when I populate the string buffer with some UTF-8 code
sequence the `0x80` and above sequences are converted to `0xFFxx` when the character is inserted
in the buffer. Hence, the test made by `report_b` will fail.  The `char` to `symbol` conversion occurs in
`str_append_ch` (the value I'm passing has the upper byte cleared by a `& 0x0FF`)

```C
extern void str_append_ch(struct str * str, char add) {

    symbol q[1];
    q[0] = add; // <<< conversion of signed character to symbol sets the upper byte
    str->data = add_to_b(str->data, 1, q);
}
```

I can come with another fix by adding the following functions:

```C
extern void str_append_symbol(struct str * str, symbol add) {

    str->data = add_to_b(str->data, 1, &add);
}

extern void write_symbol(struct generator * g, symbol s) {
    str_append_symbol(g->outbuf, s);
}
```

Then I'll use that new `write_symbol` in the Ada generator when writing the literal string.

```C
static void write_literal_string(struct generator * g, symbol * p) {
    int i;
    // Ada supports UTF-8 literal strings, we only need to escape the quote and
    // special characters.
    write_char(g, '"');
    for (i = 0; i < SIZE(p); i++) {
        int ch = p[i];
        if (ch == '"') {
            write_string(g, "\"\"");
        } else if (32 <= ch && ch < 127) {
            write_char(g, ch);
        } else if (ch <= 255) {
            write_symbol(g, ch & 0x0ff);
        } else {
            printf("In write_literal_string, can't convert p[%d] to char because it's 0x%02x\n", i, (int)p[i]);
            exit(1);
        }
    }
    write_char(g, '"');
}
```

Note, the sequence that I receive in `write_literal_string` is an UTF-8 sequence, I get 0xD0, 0xB2 which corresponds to в.

The test `if (ch < 255)` will catch incorrect literal strings.

